comments.commentBody:
@DD: I understand your point, but Dickey was traded for a AA pitcher and a AAA catcher who already has had back and knee issues that cost him half of last season. It seems like rebuilding, but by the time the field players are replenished, where will Niese, Gee and even Harvey be? It requires bringing the elements *together.* Dickey, at his age, might have another three year deal beyond the one he sought from the Mets, and which they never pursued when separated by $5M over two years. And where will Wright be when the rest of the field prospects are ready, and, other than D'Arnaud, WHO are they?<br/>
Sandomir did a lot more than make a simple implication that the Mets might spend in his article, and not a peep since. But there is NOTHING in the Mets' actions that back up Sandomir's claim. Look, I KNOW the Wilponzis are broke. I just can't fathom why they just can't sell and just go away. The payroll has shrunk by 50% since Madoff exploded. Even the Yankee$ Quixotic attempt to get to a $189M payroll threshhold for next year doesn't represent NEARLY the level of payroll cut the Mets have made, second only to the Marlins.<br/>
Empty seats at Citi, and lots of them, unless the young pitchers thrive, Santana is back to being an ace, and some outfielders and relief pitchers come out of the corn, like in Field of Dreams. The Wilpons have turned a very nice stadium into a Field of Nightmares.
